We load a file that has information about car prices and car characteristics ("CarPrice_Assignments.csv)

source : https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Automobile

First we load the data, and we display the 5 first rows. The data is seperated by commas, and the headers for each column do not need any changes. Also there is no need to skip any rows from the file.

From the above table we infer that we have 205 cars to look into. The mean symboling of the cars is around 1 so the risk rating is generally good. We deal mostly with toyota cars. Most cars from our dataset function with gas, have four doors, are sedan types, and their engine is located in the front. The mean engine size is around 127 cubic inches but the dataset include cars with fairly big and small sizes. The horsepower spans from 48 to 288 hp and there are cars that can cover 16 to 54 miles per galon of fuel. Furthermore, the peak rpm, which measures how fast the car's engine spins, is around 5200.

Thus, the dataset includes cars of all types (fast and powerful to small fuel-efficient), so the price differs among them. There are very expensive and low-price cars, which will enable us to do a rich analysis on their price.

Due to the fact that some variables are 3 orders of magnitude like peakrpm and some others are 1 order such as boreratio, we normalize all the numeric variables with the "min-max" way so that all numeric variables span from 0 to 1.

In[9]:
df['symboling'] = (df['symboling']-df['symboling'].min())/(df['symboling'].max()-df['symboling'].min())
df['wheelbase'] = (df['wheelbase']-df['wheelbase'].min())/(df['wheelbase'].max()-df['wheelbase'].min())
df['carlength'] = (df['carlength']-df['carlength'].min())/(df['carlength'].max()-df['carlength'].min())
df['carwidth'] = (df['carwidth']-df['carwidth'].min())/(df['carwidth'].max()-df['carwidth'].min())
df['carheight'] = (df['carheight']-df['carheight'].min())/(df['carheight'].max()-df['carheight'].min())

From this short analysis we infer that there is no big difference in price between cars that function with diesel regarding the aspiration. Now, we utilize box plots and anova tests in order to decide which categorical variables influence mostly the car's price and then apply to those an anova (analysis of variance). If the scores of the anova suggest that the categorical variable affects significantly the price then we will proceed with a one-hot encoding.

In[12]:
# check fueltype ################################################
import seaborn as sns
sns.boxplot(x='fueltype',y='price',data=df)
plt.title('fuel type')
plt.show()
plt.close()

import scipy.stats as stats
df_fueltype = df[['fueltype','price']]
df_grp_fueltype = df_fueltype.groupby(['fueltype'])
anova_fueltype = stats.f_oneway(df_grp_fueltype.get_group('gas')['price'],df_grp_fueltype.get_group('diesel')['price'])
print('F-score=',anova_fueltype[0],'p-value=',anova_fueltype[1])
###################################################################

# check aspiration ################################################

plt.title('aspiration')
plt.show()
plt.close()

df_aspiration = df[['aspiration','price']]
df_grp_aspiration = df_aspiration.groupby(['aspiration'])
anova_aspiration = stats.f_oneway(df_grp_aspiration.get_group('std')['price'],df_grp_aspiration.get_group('turbo')['price'])
print('F-score=',anova_aspiration[0],'p-value=',anova_aspiration[1])

# we want to check if there are enough entries of ohcv & ohc
df_enginetype_counts = df['enginetype'].value_counts().to_frame()
df_enginetype_counts.rename(columns={'enginetype':'counts'},inplace=True)
df_enginetype_counts.index.name='enginetype'

The above analysis shows that:

  1. The categorical variable "doornumber" should not be taken into consideration since the variance and median values of "two" and "four" values overlap and are close, respectively.
  2. The "fueltype" variable has values which variance overlap to a great degree, but their median values differ. Since we are not sure if we want to exclude this variable we proceed with an anova test which shows a small F-score (around 2.2 but we would ideally like an F-score>2.5) and high p-value while the desire would be less than 0.05. Thus, we exclude that variable from our predictive statistical model.
  3. The same as bove applies to "drivewheel". This variable deduced a relatively low F-score (2.3) and a high p-value (0.13). So it is excluded.
  4. The variable "fuelsystem" will be included in the model. The F-score between the 2 values that their variances do not overlap is around 71 and the p-value is of the order of -13. Also, the number of cars that belong to these 2 values are 94 and 66, which are big proportions (45% and 32%) of the total number of cars (205 --> 100%). We do one-hot encoding for this variable.
  5. Even though the "enginelocation" gives us a large F-score and a very small p-value for its 2 values, we will exclude it from our model because the "rear" value refers to only 3 cars in our dataset. If we want to keep our model simple and not burden it with many predictors we may leave that variable out (at least for the first steps of the model construction).
  6. The opposite is true about the variable 'aspiration' (which deduces a fairly large F-score and a low p-value (6.6 and 0.04, respectively) ), which its 2 values even though they do not have the same proportion of the total amount of cars, the smallest proportion is not negligible ("turbo" cars are 37 out of 205 (18%) ). So we will include that variable in our model.
  7. Regarding the "carbody" and "enginetype" variables, their values that can calculate a large F-score and a low p-value correspond to only a low proportion of cars ('hardtop'&'convertible' are only 14 cars and 'ohcv' corresponds to only 13 cars (slightly above 6% of the total population). Thus, we may consider those two variables only at the end of the model construction.

We continue with the numerical variables to examine which influence mostly the car's price. We will base our analysis on scatter plots to examine their relationship, and calculate the Pearson correlation coefficient if we detect any linear relationship between the price and the examined variable.

Before we proceed with the car's price analysis it is intersting to see that: engine size, horsepower, curbweight are positive correlated with each other but negatively correlated with highway and city km/L. As it was expected cars with big engine size will have a lot of curbweight and result in high horsepower. But, these cars will not cover many km per fuel liter as they are not designed to be fuel-efficient.

Back to our analysis, we infer from the figures that there is not clear relationship between "symboling","carheight","stroke","compressionratio","peakrpm" and price. There are no clear regression lines (which represents a function between our numeric var and price) that we can draw on these scatter plots. Thus, we exclude these variables from our model.

On the other hand, "wheelbase", "carlength", "carwidth", "curbweight", "cylindernumber", "enginesize", "horsepower", "city-km/L", and "highway-km/L" are variables that can be linearly correlated with price and we can assume a linear function that relates these variables with price. We notice that the relationship of these variables with price is more evident at low values rather than at high values where the points are more scattered. This is opposite for the case of the variables city and highway km/L where the relationship is vague at low values. Also, a quadratic function could better fit the carlength-price scatter plot.

Nevertheless, this is a good starting point and we calculate the pearson correlation coefficient assuming that a linear relationship with price is a good approximation of the truth. We will accept numeric variables that deduce correlation coefficients for price which are over ~0.7. Thus, we will consider:

  1. enginesize (corr coef = + 0.87)
  2. curbweight (corr coef = + 0.83)
  3. horsepower (corr coef = + 0.80)
  4. carwidth (corr coef = + 0.75)
  5. cylinder number (corr coef = + 0.71)
  6. carlength (corr coef = + 0.68)
  7. highway-km/L (corr coef = -0.69)
  8. city-km/L (corr coef = -0.68)
  1. The first model we are going to build is a Single Linear Regression (SLR), with which we will try to predict car's price using as predictor the enginesize.
  2. The second model will be a Multi Linear Regression (MLR), which will predict price based on enginesize, curbweight, and horsepower.
  3. The third model will be a MLR, which will predict price based on enginesize, curbweight, horsepower, and cylindernumber.
  4. The fourth model will be a MLR, which will predict the price based on carwidth, and carlength.
  5. The fifth model will be a MLR, which will predict the price based on enginesize, curbweight, horsepower, cylindernumber, carwidth, carlength.
  6. The sixth model will be a SLR, which will predict the price based on highway-km/L.
  7. The seventh model will be a MLR, which will predict the price based on highway-km/L, and city-km/L.
  8. The eight model will be a MLR, which will use all the aforementioned numerical variables.
  9. The ninth model will be a one dimensional Polynomial second order, which will use as a predictor the carlength.
  10. The tenth model will be a two dimensional Polynomial second order, which will be based on carlength, and enginesize.

Lets start with the 1st model - SLR:enginesize

# we define predictor (X) and response variable (Y)
X_data_1 = df[['enginesize']]; Y_data_1 = df['price']

# we split the data into a training set (X_train, Y_train) and a test set (X_test, Y_test)
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train_1,X_test_1,Y_train_1,Y_test_1 = train_test_split(X_data_1,Y_data_1,test_size=0.3,random_state=0)

# we fit the SLM to the train set
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
SLR_1 = LinearRegression()
SLR_1.fit(X_train_1,Y_train_1)

# we make our prediction using the train and test set
Y_hat_in_1 = SLR_1.predict(X_train_1)
Y_hat_out_1 = SLR_1.predict(X_test_1)

# we conduct the in-sample evaluation by calculating the MSE and R_squared
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
MSE_in_1 = mean_squared_error(Y_train_1,Y_hat_in_1)
print("MSE in-sample=",MSE_in_1)
R_in_1 = SLR_1.score(X_train_1,Y_train_1)
print("R^2 in-sample=",R_in_1)

# we conduct the out-of-smaple evaluation by calculating the mean R_squared from cross-validation with 3 partitions of our data
MSE_out_1 = mean_squared_error(Y_test_1,Y_hat_out_1)
print("MSE out-of-sample=",MSE_out_1)
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
scores = cross_val_score(SLR_1,X_data_1,Y_data_1,cv=3)
R_out_1 = np.mean(scores)
print("R^2 out-of-sample=",R_out_1)

plt.scatter(X_data_1,Y_data_1,c='green',s=3)
plt.plot(X_train_1,Y_hat_in_1,c='blue',label="in-sample prediction",linewidth=7.0)
plt.plot(X_test_1,Y_hat_out_1,label="out-of-smaple prediction",c='red')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('normalized engine size')
plt.ylabel('price (usd)')
plt.show()

The above model is an example of an example that fitting a straight line in the data does not always work. The prediction does not even make sence for higher km/L values since the price becomes negative. Only a small portion of the dataset of highway-km/L can be predicted fairly by this regression line(~0.2 to ~0.6). A Reciprocal function F(x)=1/x should be a better fit for these data points.
